<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC"><gtr:id>63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC</gtr:id><gtr:name>John Innes Centre</gtr:name><gtr:department>Contracts Office</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Norwich Research Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Colney</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Norwich</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NR4 7UH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC"><gtr:id>63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC</gtr:id><gtr:name>John Innes Centre</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Norwich Research Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Colney</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Norwich</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NR4 7UH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/F2DDB4A0-400A-4441-88F3-5C9389AF6784"><gtr:id>F2DDB4A0-400A-4441-88F3-5C9389AF6784</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Caroline</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Dean</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=BBS%2FE%2FJ%2F000CA378"><gtr:id>C2D11716-DE7D-43D7-9DD0-C674BD280184</gtr:id><gtr:title>Maintenance of cellular memory by the Arabidopsis VRN1 protein</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>BBS/E/J/000CA378</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Modifications of a cells chromatin landscape enable cells to memorize and maintain gene expression profiles throughout many cell-cycles during development. In animals and plants the Polycomb Repressive Complex 2 (PRC2) is involved in maintaining genes in an epigenetic 'off' state. In mammals and flies a second complex, PRC1, collaborates with PRC2 to maintain silencing. Interestingly, other organisms including worms and plants lack PRC1 and it remains elusive how they achieve stable silencing. In Arabidopsis the DNA-binding protein VRN1 is a potential candidate to fulfil such a role in silencing. During a cold-induced process called vernalization, the floral repressor gene FLC is epigenetically repressed and maintained inactive by a plant PRC2 and VRN1. Lack of VRN1 does not impair PRC2 function but seems to act downstream or in parallel of PRC2, a situation analogous to animal PRC1. Moreover, as found for mammalian PRC1, VRN1 interacts with a component of the spliceosome complex, implying RNA processing in Polycomb silencing.
The above findings suggest that VRN1, despite its lack of homology with PRC1 components, functions in the stable maintenance of PRC2 mediated silencing.
My aim is to establish a solid foundation for a mechanistic understanding of VRN1 mediated gene silencing using vernalization as a model. In-depth VRN1 protein-complex analysis will be complemented by chromatin and RNA immuno-precipitations (ChIP and RIP) as well as theoretical modelling of the vernalization process. Besides addressing a long-standing question in plant epigenetics, collected data will allow comparison with the situation in non-plant systems to develop a mechanistic consensus model on maintenance of gene silencing in different kingdoms. Notably, for both plants and humans, fundamental knowledge of epigenetics will facilitate the modulation of gene expression to; increase yield and disease resistance in crops and develop treatments for diseases, such as cancer, in humans.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-02-28</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_PROJECTED</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>140459</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>This Marie Curie fellowship provided comprehensive training to Dr Bas Rutjens in genetics, chromatin biochemistry and epigenetics. He returned to Holland to take up a position with Dr Ben Scheres in Utrecht (lab now in Wageningen). Two publications still need to be fully completed and submitted.</gtr:description><gtr:id>C6F6D4DE-3367-43FA-A7DB-F740F3436D1F</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes/><gtr:outcomeId>5458ed23ddcb28.31892447</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This project continued the functional analysis of VRN1 as a component of the machinery that epigenetically silences the floral repressor FLC during and after vernalization. The approach used was to characterize VRN1 protein partners using tandem affinity purification followed by LC-MS analysis. The results showed VRN1 does not function in a complex tightly associated with other proteins. VRN1 was identified as a yeast two hybrid interactor with CDC5, and this was independently validated by the Koncz lab (Koeln). This suggests VRN1 associates more transiently with the PRP19 RNA processing complex in the nucleus. 

In addition we pursued the finding that vrn1 mutants hyperaccumulate H2AZ histones at FLC. Extensive molecular and genetic analysis revealed that vrn1 mutants show higher nucleosome turnover than wild type plants. This suggested a mechanism of how vrn1 disrupted FLC expression both before and after vernalization. 

ChIP analysis was used to demonstrate that VRN1 preferentially bound to nucleosome free regions at FLC and this was validated across the whole genome using ChIP-seq protocols.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Conceptual understanding will be relevant for all researchers studying chromatin regulation</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>6223C6CE-FCF8-4AE4-B2EE-D51AD43670BC</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5459115314e067.40861491</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>16313E63-5E44-42B5-8A34-E8967ABF98B0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Detecting histone modifications in plants.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Methods in molecular biology (Clifton, N.J.)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/632ff335bffe1c10f52efc3566557cd9"><gtr:id>632ff335bffe1c10f52efc3566557cd9</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Song J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-1-62703-772-3</gtr:isbn><gtr:issn>1064-3745</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>543fc1a69a76f0.73565825</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>714435FF-B5FE-4DE6-8DD6-25D89AFD2B45</gtr:id><gtr:title>RNA Binding Proteins RZ-1B and RZ-1C Play Critical Roles in Regulating Pre-mRNA Splicing and Gene Expression during Development in Arabidopsis.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Plant cell</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/131f1e500d0d5a44eb53b0062c6d254e"><gtr:id>131f1e500d0d5a44eb53b0062c6d254e</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Wu Z</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1040-4651</gtr:issn><gtr:outcome